    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what do u mean by the goblin part? i'm just trying to understand the physics of the air pressure. also what happens if the tube gets something stuck in it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the earlier confusion! I was just trying to keep my thoughts on the goblin train, but I can certainly explain the physics clearly without the extra goblin metaphors.\n\nHere is how the physics actually works:\n\nA **Pitot tube** measures airspeed by comparing two different pressures. It has two openings:\n1.  **The Pitot Opening:** This faces directly into the oncoming airflow. As the plane moves, this air gets compressed and heated, creating a higher pressure (called *total pressure*).\n2.  **The Static Port:** This is usually on the side of the tube, parallel to the airflow. It measures the ambient air pressure surrounding the plane (*static pressure*).\n\nThe instrument calculates the **dynamic pressure** by subtracting the static pressure from the total pressure. Using Bernoulli's principle, this pressure difference is directly related to the speed of the air moving over the plane. The faster the plane goes, the greater the difference in pressure, and the higher the indicated airspeed.\n\n**What happens if something gets stuck in the tube?**\nIf debris, ice, or a bird part gets stuck in the Pitot opening, it blocks the airflow from reaching the sensor.",
